ment, Jews had a vested interest in military affairs. Spanning Europe, North America, and the Middle East, Penslar discusses the myths and realities of Jewish draft dodging, how Jews reacted to facing their coreligionists in battle, the careers of Jewish officers and their reception in the Jewish community, the effects of World War I on Jewish veterans, and Jewish participation in the Spanish Civil War and World War II. Penslar culminates with a study of Israel's War of Independence as a Jewish world war, which drew on the military expertise and financial support of a mobilized, global Jewish community. He considers how military service was a central issue in debates about Jewish emancipation and a primary indicator of the position of Jews in any given society. Deconstructing old stereotypes, Jews and the Military radically transforms our understanding of Jews' historic relationship to war and military power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJewish soldierszEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aJewish soldierszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxCultural assimilationzEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aJewsxCultural assimilationzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszEuropexIdentity. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aArab states.  aAshkenazic Jews.  aEuropean armies.  aFranco-Prussian War.  aFrench revolutionary wars.  aFrench-Jewish communities.  aGerman-Jewish communities.  aHabsburg armies.  aHolocaust.  aInternational Brigades.  aIsrael.  aIsraeliАalestinian conflict.  aJewish Enlightenment.  aJewish collective memory.  aJewish commonality.  aJewish community.  aJewish emancipation.  aJewish life.  aJewish military careerism.  aJewish military officers.  aJewish military units.